Czech Discovery: A Substance That Takes Up ‘HIV’ Viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists test new compounds that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the enhanced substance is that it also takes on viruses that have already gained immunity against drugs.
This fact in some cases surpasses the fact that the compound on the common variant of the virus does not act as strong as some already available medications.
AIDS cannot be cured.
However, patients can significantly extend the life of a mixture of drugs that prevent the reproduction of HIV in the body.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of the reproduction of the virus has also resulted in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which medications are already ineffective.
The work of experts from the three institutions of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, from VŠCHT Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to cope with the resistance of the virus.
They have shown that substances called metalcarborans act on the protein responsible for the reproduction of HIV.
Metal-carborans are compounds of bor, hydrogen, carbon and kobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all today used drugs, and therefore they can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists come with new ‘upgrade’ compounds prepared on the basis of the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their connection to viral protein.
Metal-carborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-wall cave formed by the atoms of bor, hydrogen and carbon are connected by a metal atom, in this case by a kobalt.
Destroy and resistant viruses
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV-protease caused by the fragmentation of the HIV virus, mature infectious viral particles would not arise.
When we stop HIV protease, we stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In a work published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is further systematically modified.
A little weaker but more reliable.
The effect of this series of HIV protease substances has been tested in the test machine and also against its resistant (resistant) variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metalcarborans on the common enzyme variant is not as strong as in clinically used medications, but it does not lose its effect for resistant variants against which the medications are often ineffective.
