The Turkish justice has dissolved for the Kurdish party and this decision has severe consequences.
The Turkish Constitutional Court on Friday decided to abolish the main pro-Kurdish party in the country. This decision immediately triggered protest and demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the southeastern part of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could significantly complicate the task of a government trying to give the Kurdish community a friendly hand and try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Party for the Democratic Society (DTP) was dissolved because it has become "the nest of activities threatening the independence of the state and its inseparable unity," Supreme Court chairman Hasim Kilic told reporters after four days of talks.
The decision was unanimously adopted by 11 judges, where the dissolution of the party needed a majority of seven votes, Kiliç said, adding that 37 party cadres including its president Ahmet Turka and deputy Aysela Tuglukova have a ban to participate in political life for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the abolition of the parliamentary immunity used by Mr. Türk and Mrs. Tugluk and the confiscation of the party’s property by the Ministry of Finance.
The DTP Party has 21 seats (from 500) in Parliament.
The party’s leadership has already warned before the verdict that the parliamentarians would rather leave the Parliament than act in it as non-political parliamentarians.
The decision is a continuation of the 2007 prosecution initiated by the prosecutor of the cassation court, Abdurrahman Yalcinkay, who accuses the DTP of obedience to the “orders” of the Working Party of Kurdistan (PKK), which Ankara and many countries consider a terrorist organization.
Many observers are convinced that the DTP is a legal political vitrine of the PKK rebels.
The party assures that it has no "basic connection" with the PKK, but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court’s judgment comes when the government gives the Kurdish community a friendly hand and offers a series of measures to strengthen their rights and attempts to limit Kurdish support to the PKK and thus end the conflict.
The DTP leadership has confirmed that the dissolution of the party could lead to a restoration of tensions in the southeastern Anatolia, where many demonstrations have been overwhelmed in recent weeks against the conditions under which the PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan is detained in clashes with police.
Since the announcement of the judgment, thousands of protesters have gathered in front of the DTP headquarters in Diyarbakir, a large city in the southeastern part, inhabited mostly by Kurds.
Police used tear grenades and water rifles, demonstrators throw Molotov’s cocktails or shoot stones from the stairs.
About a hundred people demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict was issued, Mr. Türk said that the judgment of justice would only “deep disappointment.”
Turkey cannot resolve this issue by the party’s ban, he said in the press.
The government, made up of a party emerging from the Islamist movement, also condemned this decision.
We are against the disruption of parties.
Nothing solves this, Energy Minister Taner Yildiz said.
