75% of working mothers have maternity-related work problems.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among younger-year-old women who intend to have a child.
This is the result of the study 'Fertility and the Occupational Career of Spanish Women' conducted by CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The study included 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 and the results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities on the labour market due to maternity.
The study emphasizes that at the beginning of a partnership there are many differences in views on the number of children depending on whether they work or not, and also on the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have a stable job, begin to live with a partner earlier, first give birth to the first child and overall have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, partner life and maternity are delayed, and have fewer descendants.
“Women aged 35 to 49 with stable employment have the first child in an average of 3.7 years from the beginning of coexistence with a partner. This figure is 4.1 in the case of women whose achievement of their stable employment spent most of their lives and therefore had to postpone the coexistence and the arrival of children.
The type of profession also has a strong influence on maternity, although less influence on the start time of co-life with a partner,” explains Margarita Delgado, who is dedicated to research at CSIC.
Another factor affecting the age of women at the time of marriage and the birth of the descendants is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the degree of education, the higher the age for women to marry and have their first child.
There are also differences between women of the same generation.
For example, in the age group 35 to 49 years, women with basic and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25.1 or 32.1.
“There is another difference between women depending on their degree of education.
Women with basic education marry and give birth to their first child even before they find a stable job, while women with secondary or higher education progress the opposite prefer to get a stable job, before marriage and the birth of their first child,” Delgado said.
