The help system at the manual brake is already an obligatory equipment.
As in the case of the ABS anti-blocking system it will also be with the stability control of the ESP,with the help of manual brake systems, all this will become the mandatory equipment of European cars.
In fact, they are already part of the mandatory equipment for all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for others a deadline for the removal of the defect is set, which is February 2011.
The measures introduced in the EU are aimed at increasing the protection of pedestrians, while functioning in a way that can help prevent numerous crashes.
The hand brake assistant system increases the pressure on the brakes in an emergency, which the system discovers after the driver slopes.
But it is not always able to keep this pressure up to the end.
According to a study conducted by Bosch, one-third of the drivers who suffered an accident did not stick the brake before the collision and half of them did not fully use the brake power.
1,100 accidents
On the contrary, this assistance requires the maximum from the brake system, shortening the brake distance of the vehicle.
According to a study conducted in the EU itself, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of equipment, up to 1,100 pedestrian-related deaths per year could be avoided.
Reducing this number will be even more markant – according to calculations it would prevent one of four accidents with impact on people – after the introduction of so-called intelligent hands-on brake systems.
In this case, the vehicle will be equipped with a system that (with the help of a radar or camera) captures obstacles and reports them to the driver, except for light braking.
If the driver responds, it will help him to increase the pressure on the pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond, even when the collision cannot be prevented, the device will impact the brake as intensively as possible and reduce the risk of damage to a minimum.
